title: Fellow Fireside Chat Replay: Getting into the ICS/OT Cybersecurity Field
description:
***Curious about a career in Industrial Control Systems (ICS) and Operational Technology (OT) cybersecurity? Whether you're a student, early-career professional, or someone transitioning from IT or engineering, this Fellow Fireside Chat is designed to give you real-world insights into breaking into and thriving in this critical and rapidly evolving field.***
***Join us for an engaging conversation with seasoned professionals who have successfully navigated their paths into ICS/OT cybersecurity. They'll share personal stories, lessons learned, and practical advice on building relevant skills, networking effectively, and standing out to employers.***

***Expect a candid and inspiring discussion covering:***
***\*How our panelists got started in ICS/OT cybersecurity***
***\*Key skills and certifications that make a difference***
***\*The importance of understanding industrial environments***
***\*Tips for job seekers and career changers***
***\*What makes this field uniquely rewarding (and challenging)***

***Whether you're just starting out or looking to pivot your career, this session is your chance to ask questions, get inspired, and take the next step toward a meaningful career in securing the systems that power our world.***

***Who Should Attend:***
***\*Students and recent graduates***
***\*IT/cybersecurity professionals exploring ICS/OT***
***\*Engineers and technicians looking to shift into cybersecurity***
***\*Anyone interested in protecting critical infrastructure***

title: WSDG January Technical Presentation
description:
Hexagonal and Screaming Architecture in .NET
by Brandon Atkinson

Abstract:
Hexagonal architecture is an architectural pattern designed to create loosely coupled application components that can seamlessly connect to their software environment using ports and adapters. This approach makes components interchangeable at any level and facilitates test automation, offering a robust alternative to the traditional layered architecture. In hexagonal architecture, each component communicates with others through well-defined "ports," following a specified interface to ensure loose coupling and flexibility.

Screaming architecture, a concept introduced by Robert Martin (Uncle Bob), emphasizes that a software system‚Äôs structure should clearly communicate its purpose. Much like a building blueprint reveals the function of a structure, a well-designed software architecture should make its intent immediately apparent.

In this talk, we will briefly explore both hexagonal and screaming architecture patterns, then dive into code to see how these concepts can be applied to a modern .NET codebase. Additionally, we will discuss how these architectural principles can assist in planning and estimating work more effectively.

Bio:
Brandon Atkinson is a software engineer with more than 20 years of experience in the field. He has authored books, been a Microsoft MVP (in SharePoint!), and holds a patent for CI/CD pipelines. He loves tinkering with code, and spends his time with his family in Richmond, VA.

description:
**From single prompts to coordinated AI teams**

AI agents are moving beyond simple chatbots. In this talk, you will see how multi-agent systems work together to reason, plan, and execute complex tasks. Using CrewAI as the framework, we will explore practical patterns that scale from experiments to real production use cases across engineering, operations, and knowledge work.

This session blends concepts with live examples so attendees leave with both understanding and inspiration.

**üîç What you‚Äôll learn**

* What multi-agent systems are and why they matter now
* Core agent roles such as planners, executors, reviewers, and coordinators
* How CrewAI structures collaboration between agents
* Practical demos that show agents working together on real problems
* How the same agent setup can be adapted for resumes, sales workflows, ops automation, and internal tooling
* Where multi-agent systems break down and how to design around common pitfalls

**üéôÔ∏è Your speaker**
**[Tim Masterson](https://www.linkedin.com/in/tim-masterson-a202574/)**

Principal Architect of Streaming at Paramount+ and Pluto TV

Tim leads large-scale distributed systems powering millions of users across major streaming platforms. He brings deep experience in system architecture, AI-assisted workflows, and production-grade engineering. His focus is not hype, but how emerging AI patterns actually work when reliability, scale, and teams matter.

**üë• Who should attend?**

* Software engineers and architects
* Product managers and technical founders

* Students and job seekers curious about agent-based systems

No prior CrewAI experience required.

**üí° Why this matters**
Single-prompt AI tools are reaching their limits. The next wave of useful AI comes from systems where multiple agents collaborate, critique, and adapt. Understanding how to design and reason about these systems now puts you ahead of where AI-powered products and workflows are heading.

**ü§ù A social networking night for AI, automation, and curious minds**

AI After Dark is a relaxed, social-first networking event designed to bring together people across Hampton Roads who are curious about artificial intelligence, machine learning, automation, vibecoding, and the future of technology.

This is not a lecture. This is not a pitch night.

It is a space to connect, explore ideas, and meet others who are building, learning, experimenting, or simply trying to understand where all of this is headed.

Whether you are brand new to AI or have been working in the field for years, you belong here.

**‚Äã‚ú® What to expect**

* Casual, open networking with a diverse mix of builders, creatives, technologists, founders, students, and professionals
* Organic conversations around AI, ML, automation, no-code, low-code, and emerging tools

title: 10 Years A Kotlin Dev
description:
Kotlin has emerged as a compelling choice for both Android and backend development, offering a modern language with strong null-safety, concise syntax, and excellent interoperability with Java. In this meetup, we'll explore the key advantages that drive teams to adopt Kotlin‚Äîfrom improved developer productivity and safer Android apps to structured concurrency with coroutines on the backend. We'll highlight how Kotlin aligns with today's Android ecosystem, integrates with popular backend frameworks, and enables cleaner, more maintainable code across platforms. At the same time, adopting Kotlin is not without challenges. We'll take an honest look at the tradeoffs, including learning curve considerations, build performance, interoperability friction with legacy Java code, and operational concerns in backend systems. Through a retrospective lens, this talk will share practical lessons learned and guidance on when Kotlin is the right choice‚Äîand when it may not be‚Äîhelping attendees make informed decisions for their Android and server-side projects.
